  Make new folder             ----                 $  mkdir ~/Downloads/new-folder
(Inside Downloads)
                                                 
                                                 
 Make new folder with       ----                 $  sudo mkdir ~/Downloads/new-folder
 write protected

Delete any folder           ----                 $  rm -R ~/Downloads/new-folder

Delete file named 'x.txt'   ----                 $  rm x.txt

Create empty file 'x.txt'  
under '/var/wwww/html'           ----            $  sudo touch /var/www/html/x.txt

copy one file content in another file      ------  $ cp first_file another_file


copy any file in any folder where folder's path is : /any_folder/          --------     $ cp any_file /any_folder/








$ cat glaciers.txt > rivers.txt                        ////// overwrites
cat rivers.txt
$ cat glaciers.txt >> rivers.txt                       //////  appends
cat rivers.txt

$ cat < lakes.txt

cat volcanoes.txt | wc                               | is a "pipe". The | takes the standard output of the command on the left, and pipes it as standard input to the command on the right.| redirects standard output of a command to another command.

                                                    wc- in turn, the wc command outputs the number of lines, words, and characters in volcanoes.txt, 

$ sort lakes.txt
$ cat lakes.txt | sort > sorted-lakes.txt
uniq deserts.txt                                   /////////uniq stands for "unique" and filters out adjacent, duplicate lines in a file.
sort deserts.txt | uniq
sort deserts.txt | uniq > uniq-deserts.txt

$ grep Mount mountains.txt                          ///////It searches files for lines that match a pattern and returns the results.
$ grep -i Mount mountains.txt



$ sed 's/snow/rain/' forests.txt                  /////////In this case, sed searches forests.txt for the word "snow" and replaces it 	                                                      with "rain." Importantly, the above command will only replace the first instance                                                of "snow" on a line.






$ sed 's/snow/rain/g' forests.txt          ///////All instances of "snow" on a line will be turned to "rain"

